Source:
C Programming for Everybody - RS-4: Reading Lines of Input

Question:
Write a C program equivalent to this Python program

Python Code:
print('Enter line')
line = input()
print('Line:', line)

C Code:
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    char line[1000];

    printf("Enter line\n");
    scanf("%[^\n]1000s", line);
    printf("Line: %s\n", line);
}

Input:
Hello world - have a nice day

Output:
Enter line
Line: Hello world - have a nice day

Notes:
- Regular expressions [^\n] match any character thats not a new line  
- scanf(“%[^\n]1000s”, line) -> read a whole line but stop at 1000 characters 

############################################################################################################

Source:
C Programming for Everybody - RS-5: Reading Lines of Input with fgets()

Question:
Write a C program to implement this Python program, using the fgets function instead of scanf.

Python Code:
print('Enter line')
line = input()
print('Line:', line)

C Code:
#include <stdio.h>

int main() {
    char line[1000];

    printf("Enter line\n");
    fgets(line, 1000, stdin);
    printf("Line: %s\n", line);
}

Input:
Hello world - have a nice day

Output:
Enter line
Line: Hello world - have a nice day

Notes:
- fgets(buffer, sizeof(buffer), stdin); 
- Buffer: point to character array where input will be stored 
- Sizeof(buffer): maximum number of characters to read including null terminator 
- Stdin: input stream to read from, stdin represents standard input 

